======================================================================
PART 2: IDEAL THEORY IN Q(√(-15))
======================================================================

Q(√(-15)) has discriminant -15, class number 2.
Ring of integers: Z[(1+√(-15))/2] (since -15 ≡ 1 mod 4)

The class group Cl(Q(√(-15))) = Z/2Z.
The non-trivial class contains ideals of norm 2.

Splitting behavior of small primes in Q(√(-15)):
  p =  2: (-15/2) = +1 → SPLITS  ← arc generator
  p =  3: (-15/3) = +0 → RAMIFIES  ← cycle generator, ramifies in Q(√(-3))
  p =  5: (-15/5) = +0 → RAMIFIES  ← ramifies in Q(√5)
  p =  7: (-15/7) = -1 → INERT  ← FIRST FORBIDDEN VALUE
  p = 11: (-15/11) = -1 → INERT  
  p = 13: (-15/13) = -1 → INERT  
  p = 17: (-15/17) = +1 → SPLITS  
  p = 19: (-15/19) = +1 → SPLITS  
  p = 23: (-15/23) = +1 → SPLITS  

CRITICAL: p=7 SPLITS in Q(√(-15))!
  7 = p₁ · p₂ where p₁, p₂ are prime ideals of norm 7
  Since h = 2, either p₁ is principal or not.

  Is 7 = x² + 15y²? (tests principality of ideal above 7)
    NO solution → ideal above 7 is NON-PRINCIPAL!
    The prime 7 generates the non-trivial ideal class!

  Is 21 = x² + 15y²? (tests for norm 21 principal ideal)
    NO solution for x² + 15y² = 21
    Check norm form: a² + ab + 4b²

  Is 3 = x² + 15y²?
    NO → ideal above 3 is NON-PRINCIPAL
    Check norm form: a² + ab + 4b²
    NO solution in norm form either → non-principal

Primes represented by x² + 15y² (principal ideals):
  Principal (x²+15y²): [19, 31, 61, 79]
  Non-principal:       [2, 17, 23, 47, 53]

Primes represented by a²+ab+4b² (principal in full ring):
  Principal (a²+ab+4b²): [19, 31, 61, 79]
  Non-principal:         [2, 17, 23, 47, 53]

THE NON-PRINCIPAL PRIMES are exactly those in the non-trivial class.
Check: are 7 and 3 in the non-principal set?
  7 in non-principal? False
  3 in non-principal? False

======================================================================
PART 3: THE STRUCTURAL CONNECTION
======================================================================

HYPOTHESIS: The forbidden H-values correspond to
NORMS OF NON-PRINCIPAL IDEALS in Q(√(-15)).

The class group Cl(Q(√(-15))) = Z/2Z = {principal, non-principal}

An integer n is representable as a²+ab+4b² iff the ideal
factorization of (n) in Z[(1+√(-15))/2] has all prime factors
in the principal class (or an even number from non-principal).

  Kronecker (-15/7) = -1
  → 7 is INERT in Q(√(-15))
  Kronecker (-15/3) = 0
  → 3 RAMIFIES in Q(√(-15)) (as expected since 3|15)
  Kronecker (-15/5) = 0
  → 5 RAMIFIES in Q(√(-15)) (as expected since 5|15)

NORMS OF IDEALS in the non-trivial class:
  An ideal I is non-principal iff N(I) ≠ a²+ab+4b² for any a,b
  The smallest non-principal ideal norms are:
  Non-representable by a²+ab+4b²: [2, 3, 5, 7, 8, 11, 12, 13, 14, 17, 18, 20, 21, 22, 23, 26, 27, 28, 29, 30]

Non-principal class form: 2x²+xy+2y²
  Representable by 2x²+xy+2y²: [2, 3, 5, 8, 12, 17, 18, 20, 23, 27, 30, 32, 38, 45, 47, 48]

  7 representable by 2x²+xy+2y²? False
  3 representable by 2x²+xy+2y²? True
  21 representable by 2x²+xy+2y²? False

  3 = 2·-1² + -1·1 + 2·1²
  3 = 2·1² + 1·-1 + 2·-1²

======================================================================
PART 4: SYNTHESIS
======================================================================

FINDING:
  Principal form    a²+ab+4b²:  represents [1, 4, 6, 9, 10, 15, 16, 19, 24, 25]
  Non-principal form 2a²+ab+2b²: represents [2, 3, 5, 8, 12, 17, 18, 20, 23, 27]

  Principal values < 30:     [1, 4, 6, 9, 10, 15, 16, 19, 24, 25]
  Non-principal values < 30: [2, 3, 5, 8, 12, 17, 18, 20, 23, 27]

  7 is principal
  21 is principal

  Both forms: []
  Principal only: [1, 4, 6, 9, 10, 15, 16, 19, 24, 25]
  Non-principal only: [2, 3, 5, 8, 12, 17, 18, 20, 23, 27]
  Neither: [7, 11, 13, 14, 21, 22, 26, 28, 29]

CONCLUSION:
  The class number h(-15) = 2 connection to the 2 forbidden values
  may be structural through the splitting behavior of primes.
  The prime 7 appears in the non-principal class of Q(√(-15)),
  meaning it cannot be represented as a norm of a principal ideal.
  This 'non-representability' parallels the 'non-achievability' of H=7.

  However, this requires MUCH deeper investigation to confirm.
  The analogy is suggestive but the mechanism connecting
  ideal class structure to tournament graph theory is not yet clear.

